      "published_date": "2025-04-08T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "Duke Energy Ohio \nKentucky\nDayton Power and \nLight\nOhio Valley Electric \nCorporation\nDuquesne Light\nAmerican \nTransmission \nSystems\nBaltimore Gas and \nElectric\nPepco\nDelmarva Power \nand Light\nMet-Ed\nPPL Electric \nUtilities\nAtlantic City \nElectric\nPECO Energy\nJersey Central \nPower and Light\nPSE&G\nRockland Electric\nEast Kentucky\nPower\nCooperative\nComEd\nDominion\nAllegheny\nPower\nSystems\nAmerican\nElectric\nPower\nKeeping the Lights On\nWe’re sometimes called air traffic controllers of the \npower grid. PJM monitors and coordinates more than \n1,400 generating sources and 88,333 miles of high-voltage \ntransmission lines. Just like air traffic controllers, we don’t \nown the equipment we direct. Others own the power lines \nand power plants.\nPower generators, utilities and power marketers coordinate \ntheir operations through PJM. Doing so makes major electric \noutages less likely to occur and reduces power costs.\nData Link\nP sJM Control \nCenters\nGenerators\nHigh-Voltage\nSubstations Transmission Lines",
